   <text>
      <body>
         <head>To <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1117.xml"/>Mr. I&apos;Ans.</persName><note
               place="foot" n="1">The manuscript is possibly abbreviating the name I&apos;Anson.
                  <persName>Thomas</persName> and <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1117.xml"
                  />Bryan I&apos;Anson</persName>, brothers who shared a legal practice in
                  <placeName>Westminster</placeName> and often assisted the Wesley brothers (see
               21:308, n. 73 in this edn.), are possible recipients, though it is not clear they
               would be in <placeName>Bristol</placeName>.</note></head>
         <opener><placeName>London</placeName><lb/><date when="1759-12-11">December 11, 1759</date><lb/><lb/>
            <salute>Sir,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p><pb n="181"/>I return you thanks for transmitting that letter to me. I am glad our
            little service was so well accepted.<note place="foot" n="2">I.e., assistance in
               providing winter clothing for French prisoners held in <placeName>Knowle</placeName>,
               described in the letters of <date when="1759-10-20">Oct. 20</date> and <date
                  when="1759-11-04">Nov. 4</date> above.</note> If I should see
               <placeName>Bristol</placeName> again before those poor men return home, I would use
            what interest I have in order to assist them a little farther. I am, sir,</p>
         <closer><signed>Your most humble servant,<lb/><persName>John
            Wesley</persName></signed></closer>
      </body>
   </text>
